Week 5 — Day 1: LeetCode 46 — Permutations

Problem Summary

Given a collection of distinct integers, return all possible permutations.
Approach

Use backtracking (depth-first search) to build permutations in-place by swapping. At each position idx we try every candidate from idx to n-1, swap it into place, recurse for idx+1, then backtrack by swapping back.

This approach is simple, efficient, and commonly used for permutation generation.

Time & Space Complexity

Time: O(n * n!) — there are n! permutations and copying each takes O(n).

Space: O(n) recursion depth plus output storage O(n!).

File: permutations.cpp
class Solution {
public:
void permu(vector<int>& nums,int idx, vector<vector<int>> &ans){
    if(idx==nums.size()){
        ans.push_back({nums});
        return;
    }
    for(int i=idx;i<nums.size();i++){
        swap(nums[idx],nums[i]);
        permu(nums,idx+1,ans);
        swap(nums[idx],nums[i]);
    }
}
    vector<vector<int>> permute(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<vector<int>> ans;
        
        permu(nums,0,ans);
        return ans;
    }
};
